PMID== 22890546
TI  == micronutrient modulation of nf-kappab in oral keratinocytes exposed to periodontal bacteria.
AB  == chronic periodontal diseases are characterised by a dysregulated and exaggerated  inflammatory/immune response to plaque bacteria. we have demonstrated previously  that oral keratinocytes up-regulate key molecular markers of inflammation, including nf-kappab and cytokine signalling, when exposed to the periodontal bacteria porphyromonas gingivalis and fusobacterium nucleatum in vitro. the purpose of the current study was to investigate whether alpha-lipoic acid was able to abrogate bacterially-induced pro-inflammatory changes in the h400 oral epithelial cell line. initial studies indicated that alpha-lipoic acid supplementation (1-4 mm) significantly reduced cell attachment; lower concentrations (<0.5 mm) enabled >85% cell adhesion at 24 h. while a pro-inflammatory response, demonstrable by nf-kappab translocation, gene expression and protein production was evident in h400 cells following exposure to p. gingivalis and f. nucleatum, pre-incubation of cells with 0.5 mm alpha-lipoic  acid modulated this response. alpha-lipoic acid pre-treatment significantly decreased levels of bacterially-induced nf-kappab activation and il-8 protein production, and differentially modulated transcript levels for il-8, il-1beta, tnf-alpha and gm-csf, tlr2, 4, 9, s100a8, s100a9, lysyl oxidase, nf-kappab1, hmox, and sod2. overall, the data indicate that alpha-lipoic acid exerts an anti-inflammatory effect on oral epithelial cells exposed to periodontal bacteria and thus may provide a novel adjunctive treatment for periodontal diseases.
TIHT== 
